13.250.109.83     -        <div class="content_section_text">
13.250.109.83     -          <p>
13.250.109.83     -                This is the default welcome page used to test the correct
13.250.109.83     -                operation of the Apache2 server after installation on Ubuntu systems.
13.250.109.83     -                It is based on the equivalent page on Debian, from which the Ubuntu Apache
13.250.109.83     -                packaging is derived.
13.250.109.83     -                If you can read this page, it means that the Apache HTTP server installed at
13.250.109.83     -                this site is working properly. You should <b>replace this file</b> (located at
13.250.109.83     -                <tt>/var/www/html/index.html</tt>) before continuing to operate your HTTP server.
13.250.109.83     -          </p>
13.250.109.83     -
13.250.109.83     -
13.250.109.83     -          <p>
13.250.109.83     -                If you are a normal user of this web site and don't know what this page is
13.250.109.83     -                about, this probably means that the site is currently unavailable due to
13.250.109.83     -                maintenance.
13.250.109.83     -                If the problem persists, please contact the site's administrator.
13.250.109.83     -          </p>
13.250.109.83     -
13.250.109.83     -        </div>
13.250.109.83     -        <div class="section_header">
13.250.109.83     -          <div id="changes"></div>
13.250.109.83     -                Configuration Overview
13.250.109.83     -        </div>
13.250.109.83     -        <div class="content_section_text">
13.250.109.83     -          <p>
13.250.109.83     -                Ubuntu's Apache2 default configuration is different from the
13.250.109.83     -                upstream default configuration, and split into several files optimized for
13.250.109.83     -                interaction with Ubuntu tools. The configuration system is
13.250.109.83     -                <b>fully documented in
13.250.109.83     -                /usr/share/doc/apache2/README.Debian.gz</b>. Refer to this for the full
13.250.109.83     -                documentation. Documentation for the web server itself can be
13.250.109.83     -                found by accessing the <a href="/manual">manual</a> if the <tt>apache2-doc</tt>
13.250.109.83     -                package was installed on this server.
13.250.109.83     -
13.250.109.83     -          </p>
13.250.109.83     -          <p>
13.250.109.83     -                The configuration layout for an Apache2 web server installation on Ubuntu systems is as follows:
13.250.109.83     -          </p>
13.250.109.83     -          <pre>
13.250.109.83     -/etc/apache2/
13.250.109.83     -|-- apache2.conf
13.250.109.83     -|       `--  ports.conf
13.250.109.83     -|-- mods-enabled
13.250.109.83     -|       |-- *.load
13.250.109.83     -|       `-- *.conf
13.250.109.83     -|-- conf-enabled
13.250.109.83     -|       `-- *.conf
13.250.109.83     -|-- sites-enabled
13.250.109.83     -|       `-- *.conf
13.250.109.83     -          </pre>
13.250.109.83     -          <ul>
13.250.109.83     -                        <li>
13.250.109.83     -                           <tt>apache2.conf</tt> is the main configuration
13.250.109.83     -                           file. It puts the pieces together by including all remaining configuration
13.250.109.83     -                           files when starting up the web server.
13.250.109.83     -                        </li>
13.250.109.83     -
13.250.109.83     -                        <li>
13.250.109.83     -                           <tt>ports.conf</tt> is always included from the
13.250.109.83     -                           main configuration file. It is used to determine the listening ports for
13.250.109.83     -                           incoming connections, and this file can be customized anytime.
13.250.109.83     -                        </li>
13.250.109.83     -
13.250.109.83     -                        <li>
13.250.109.83     -                           Configuration files in the <tt>mods-enabled/</tt>,
13.250.109.83     -                           <tt>conf-enabled/</tt> and <tt>sites-enabled/</tt> directories contain
13.250.109.83     -                           particular configuration snippets which manage modules, global configuration
13.250.109.83     -                           fragments, or virtual host configurations, respectively.
13.250.109.83     -                        </li>
13.250.109.83     -
13.250.109.83     -                        <li>
13.250.109.83     -                           They are activated by symlinking available
13.250.109.83     -                           configuration files from their respective
13.250.109.83     -                           *-available/ counterparts. These should be managed
13.250.109.83     -                           by using our helpers
13.250.109.83     -                           <tt>
13.250.109.83     -                                <a href="http://manpages.debian.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=a2enmod">a2enmod</a>,
13.250.109.83     -                                <a href="http://manpages.debian.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=a2dismod">a2dismod</a>,
13.250.109.83     -                           </tt>
13.250.109.83     -                           <tt>
13.250.109.83     -                                <a href="http://manpages.debian.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=a2ensite">a2ensite</a>,
13.250.109.83     -                                <a href="http://manpages.debian.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=a2dissite">a2dissite</a>,
13.250.109.83     -                            </tt>
13.250.109.83     -                                and
13.250.109.83     -                           <tt>
13.250.109.83     -                                <a href="http://manpages.debian.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=a2enconf">a2enconf</a>,
13.250.109.83     -                                <a href="http://manpages.debian.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=a2disconf">a2disconf</a>
13.250.109.83     -                           </tt>. See their respective man pages for detailed information.
13.250.109.83     -                        </li>
13.250.109.83     -
13.250.109.83     -                        <li>
13.250.109.83     -                           The binary is called apache2. Due to the use of
13.250.109.83     -                           environment variables, in the default configuration, apache2 needs to be
13.250.109.83     -                           started/stopped with <tt>/etc/init.d/apache2</tt> or <tt>apache2ctl</tt>.
13.250.109.83     -                           <b>Calling <tt>/usr/bin/apache2</tt> directly will not work</b> with the
13.250.109.83     -                           default configuration.
13.250.109.83     -                        </li>
13.250.109.83     -          </ul>
13.250.109.83     -        </div>
13.250.109.83     -
13.250.109.83     -        <div class="section_header">
13.250.109.83     -            <div id="docroot"></div>
13.250.109.83     -                Document Roots
13.250.109.83     -        </div>
13.250.109.83     -
13.250.109.83     -        <div class="content_section_text">
13.250.109.83     -            <p>
13.250.109.83     -                By default, Ubuntu does not allow access through the web browser to
13.250.109.83     -                <em>any</em> file apart of those located in <tt>/var/www</tt>,
13.250.109.83     -                <a href="http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.4/mod/mod_userdir.html">public_html</a>
13.250.109.83     -                directories (when enabled) and <tt>/usr/share</tt> (for web
13.250.109.83     -                applications). If your site is using a web document root
13.250.109.83     -                located elsewhere (such as in <tt>/srv</tt>) you may need to whitelist your
13.250.109.83     -                document root directory in <tt>/etc/apache2/apache2.conf</tt>.
13.250.109.83     -            </p>
13.250.109.83     -            <p>
13.250.109.83     -                The default Ubuntu document root is <tt>/var/www/html</tt>. You
13.250.109.83     -                can make your own virtual hosts under /var/www. This is different
13.250.109.83     -                to previous releases which provides better security out of the box.
13.250.109.83     -            </p>
13.250.109.83     -        </div>
13.250.109.83     -
13.250.109.83     -        <div class="section_header">

13.250.109.83     -                Reporting Problems
13.250.109.83     -        </div>
13.250.109.83     -        <div class="content_section_text">
13.250.109.83     -          <p>
13.250.109.83     -                Please use the <tt>ubuntu-bug</tt> tool to report bugs in the
13.250.109.83     -                Apache2 package with Ubuntu. However, check <a
13.250.109.83     -                href="https://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/apache2">existing
13.250.109.83     -                bug reports</a> before reporting a new bug.
13.250.109.83     -          </p>
13.250.109.83     -          <p>
13.250.109.83     -                Please report bugs specific to modules (such as PHP and others)
13.250.109.83     -                to respective packages, not to the web server itself.
13.250.109.83     -          </p>
